  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"Article","headline":"Scrabble vs Words With Friends — Key Differences","description":"Compare Scrabble and Words With Friends side by side. Understand the differences in board layout, tile values, dictionaries, scoring, and strategic implications of each game.","datePublished":"2026-06-14","author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"ScrabbleWordsFinder.com","url":"https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"ScrabbleWordsFinder.com"},"mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com/blog/scrabble-vs-words-with-friends"}})} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"What are the main differences between Scrabble and Words With Friends?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The key differences are: different board layouts (premium square positions differ), different tile values (some letters score differently), different dictionaries (WWF uses its own word list), different board sizes (both 15x15 but premium squares are repositioned), and WWF has no physical version or official tournaments. The core gameplay of forming crosswords is the same."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Is Scrabble harder than Words With Friends?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Scrabble is generally considered more strategically complex due to its premium square layout creating more dramatic scoring swings, the challenge system in tournament play, and the deeper competitive infrastructure. Words With Friends is more accessible with its social features and slightly more forgiving board design, making it popular with casual players."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Can I use Scrabble words in Words With Friends?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Not always. While most common English words are valid in both games, the dictionaries differ. Words With Friends uses its own proprietary word list that includes some words not in the Scrabble dictionary and excludes others that Scrabble accepts. Always verify words against the specific game dictionary you are playing."}}]})} />

  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <article class="prose prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose flex items-center gap-1">
        <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">← Blog</a><span class="mx-1">›</span><span class="text-gray-300">Online Scrabble</span>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Scrabble vs Words With Friends — Key Differences</h1>
      <div class="not-prose mb-8 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
        <time datetime="2026-06-14">June 14, 2026</time><span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span><span>8 min read</span><span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span><a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🔤</span> Word Finder</a>
      </div>
      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-300 mb-8">Scrabble and Words With Friends look similar at first glance — both involve forming crosswords on a grid for points. But dig deeper and you'll find meaningful differences in board design, scoring, dictionaries, and competitive ecosystems that create distinct strategic experiences. Understanding these differences helps you appreciate each game and transition skills between them effectively.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
